  {
    "abstract": "Nine years after they parted, in Vienna, at the end of &quot;Before Sunrise,&quot;  Jesse (Ethan Hawke) and Celine (Julie Delpy) rediscover each other in Paris,  and relive their brief encounter. This time, it is even briefer: the film unfolds, without skipping a minute, in the hour or so before Jess must catch a plane home to New York, and all those minutes are filled with looping, self-conscious talk as the reunited lovers wander along the Seine.   Their intimacy is tinged with nostalgic regret. The airy sense of freedom   that they shared in their early 20's has given way to the resignation of adulthood, even as they meander toward a second chance. The liberating   sweetness of the earlier movie has mellowed into a saltier, sadder flavor, but Richard Linklater, one of our most literate and intelligent directors, has not talked himself out of the possibility of romance, and the movie's relaxed, discursive structure is dense with implied feeling and oblique drama. — A. O. Scott",
    "byline": {
      "original": "By A. O. Scott"
    },
